      Oh hey it=E2=80=99s a podcast
   =20
 =20

Programming note! We are trying something new around here. It=E2=80=99s a p=
odcast. There=E2=80=99s going to be a Money Stuff podcast, in which I=E2=80=
=99ll discuss topics from that week=E2=80=99s column and other financial ne=
ws with my friend=C2=A0Katie Greifeld, a Bloomberg reporter and television =
anchor.
It will come out on Fridays, starting tomorrow, and we are all going to be =
very chill and laid-back about it? This is an experiment, we=E2=80=99ll=C2=
=A0see how it goes, and I=E2=80=99m sure it will change over time as we fig=
ure out what it is. Perhaps we=E2=80=99ll answer reader questions, probably=
 we=E2=80=99ll have guests, we=E2=80=99ll see. If you want=C2=A0Money Stuff=
, but in podcast form, then there is some chance that this will be=C2=A0the=
 podcast for you.=C2=A0
If that sounds interesting, you can check out Money Stuff: The Podcast at A=
pple, Spotify, or wherever you get your podcasts, as one says when one is a=
 podcaster. You can listen to the trailer now, and the first episode will b=
e out tomorrow afternoon.

 =20
   =20
      Hedging
   =20
 =20

If you work at a big public technology company, you might get a large chunk=
 of your pay in the form of stock in your company. Over time, you will accu=
mulate a lot of stock; a lot of your net worth might consist of shares in y=
our company. This is good,=C2=A0this is what the company wants, this aligns=
 incentives: If you own a lot of stock, you will work hard so the company d=
oes well so your stock will go up.
On the other hand, you may not like it.=C2=A0You have a lot of undiversifie=
d risk: A lot of your financial net worth is tied up in one company, and a =
lot of your human capital is tied up in that same company, and if the compa=
ny goes under you will lose everything. And while it is nice to align incen=
tives, if you are one of thousands of well-paid employees at a large public=
 tech company, there might not be all that much=C2=A0you personally=C2=A0ca=
n do to shape the company=E2=80=99s destiny.
So you might want to diversify. The easy way to do this is to sell your sto=
ck and buy an index fund. Your stock probably has vesting periods and restr=
ictions, so you can=E2=80=99t sell all it as soon as you get it, but if you=
=E2=80=99ve been there a long time you will have lots of unrestricted share=
s and can sell down.
But tech stocks mostly go up, so if you=E2=80=99ve been there a long time a=
nd are selling shares you got years ago, you will have large capital gains.=
 That=E2=80=99s nice for you, really, but it does mean you have to pay taxe=
s when you sell your stock and buy index funds.=C2=A0
On the other hand, what you could do is:
=09Start a=C2=A0partnership=C2=A0with some other people who happen to own s=
tocks in=C2=A0other=C2=A0tech companies. There are lots of those people: If=
 you=E2=80=99re a well-paid Meta engineer with a bunch of stock, you can pr=
obably find well-paid Amazon and Alphabet engineers who also own a bunch of=
 their companies=E2=80=99 stocks.=09
Contribute=C2=A0your shares to the partnership, in exchange for a stake in =
the partnership. You put in $1 million of Meta stock for 1/3 of the partner=
ship; your friends put in $1 million of Amazon and Alphabet stock in exchan=
ge for 1/3 stakes in the partnership.=09Now, instead of owning $1 million o=
f Meta stock, you own a one-third share in a somewhat more diversified $3 m=
illion pot of stocks. (And you can expand this to more stocks for more dive=
rsification.)

The advantage is that, while selling your stock for cash and then reinvesti=
ng the cash in an index fund is a taxable transaction, contributing your st=
ock to a partnership in exchange for a share of that partnership is not. An=
d if you do it right, you can make the partnership=E2=80=99s holdings look =
a lot like an index fund. (Not tax advice! It is not in fact quite as simpl=
e as this, though this is the right general idea.
  [1]
)
It is not trivial to do this right,=C2=A0for you: You have to get the techn=
ical tax structuring right, plus what are the odds that you know a bunch of=
 other engineers at other companies with exactly the right amounts of stock=
 to contribute? But with enough well-paid engineers at big public tech comp=
anies, it is sensible for someone else to do this at scale and offer it as =
a product. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=20
Eliyahu Kamisher reports:

Known as an exchange fund or a swap fund, the product is familiar to the su=
per rich. Now, share-price rallies at companies such as Meta Platforms Inc.=
 and Nvidia Corp. are creating an opportunity to offer the structure to mod=
erately wealthy techies as well, says Srikanth Narayan, founder of San Fran=
cisco-based Cache.
=E2=80=9CThe mission is to make these financial products =E2=80=93 that hav=
e typically been in the upper echelon =E2=80=93 available more broadly,=E2=
=80=9D said Narayan, a former engineer at Uber Technologies Inc. =E2=80=9CA=
ll of my friends and colleagues are talking about the same thing, which is =
that more of their net worth is tied up in a single stock.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=
=A6
Cache=E2=80=99s swap-fund offering enables participants to pool their stock=
 holdings together, creating a more diversified collection of assets. Inves=
tors then get shares of the fund equivalent to their contributions, giving =
them the benefits of more varied holdings without having to sell their stoc=
k.
There=E2=80=99s a limit to how much stock of a particular company Cache can=
 accept because the swap fund is designed to mirror the tech-heavy Nasdaq, =
Narayan said. Currently, he can bring in more Amazon.com Inc. and Microsoft=
 Corp. shares, and he=E2=80=99s seeking stock from non-tech Nasdaq companie=
s such as PepsiCo Inc. and Costco Wholesale Corp.

Here are more details from Cache. Kamisher notes that, if this really takes=
 off (so far it=E2=80=99s pretty small), it could be bad for tax revenue; C=
alifornia gets a lot of money from tech equity compensation. But that effec=
t depends on what this product=C2=A0replaces. If it replaces =E2=80=9Csell =
your stock and buy index funds,=E2=80=9D it will lower tax revenue. If it r=
eplaces =E2=80=9Cjust hold onto your stock until you retire,=E2=80=9D it wo=
n=E2=80=99t.
Me, though, I=E2=80=99m more interested in what it could do for incentives.=
 Presumably the big tech companies pay their employees with lots of stock (=
in part for accounting reasons sure but also) in order to align incentives =
and motivate the employees.
  [2]
=C2=A0You would expect that a lot of Meta employees own a lot of Meta stock=
, a lot of Alphabet employees own a lot of Alphabet stock, a lot of Amazon =
employees own a lot of Amazon stock and so forth. Each company has employee=
s with strong financial incentives =E2=80=94=C2=A0not just the desire for r=
aises and bonuses, but also the desire to increase the value of their exist=
ing stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0to help their company win in the general competiti=
on among tech giants.
But what if all of the midlevel employees of all of these companies ended u=
p owning diversified portfolios of all of them? What if workers in Big Tech=
 were compensated with, effectively, a portfolio of Big Tech Index shares? =
(Plus Costco, if Cache can find any.
  [3]
) What does that do for competition?
=E2=80=9CShould index funds be illegal,=E2=80=9D I=20
sometimes=20
ask around here: If every public company is owned by diversified investors =
who also own all of its competitors, will those companies have less incenti=
ve to compete? One of the=20
main responses to this concern is that, while the=C2=A0institutional shareh=
olders=C2=A0are mostly diversified, the=C2=A0executives and employees=C2=A0=
tend to own concentrated positions in their employers=E2=80=99 stocks, so=
=C2=A0they=C2=A0are motivated to compete. And they run the company from day=
 to day. But what if the employees were all diversified too?

