<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Programming note! We are trying something new =
around here. It=E2=80=99s a podcast. There=E2=80=99s going to be a Money St=
uff podcast, in which I=E2=80=99ll discuss topics from that week=E2=80=99s =
column and other financial news with my friend=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35003841.257348/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZ=
XJnbWVkaWEuY29tL3RhbGVudC9wZW9wbGUva2F0aWUtZ3JlaWZlbGQv/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cB71ab57e0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;">Katie Greifeld</a>, a Bloomberg reporter and televi=
sion anchor.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It will come out on Fridays, starting tomorrow=
, and we are all going to be very chill and laid-back about it? This is an =
experiment, we=E2=80=99ll=C2=A0see how it goes, and I=E2=80=99m sure it wil=
l change over time as we figure out what it is. Perhaps we=E2=80=99ll answe=
r reader questions, probably we=E2=80=99ll have guests, we=E2=80=99ll see. =
If you want=C2=A0Money Stuff, but in podcast form, then there is some chanc=
e that this will be=C2=A0the podcast for you.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If that sounds interesting, you can <a href=3D=
"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35003841.257348/aHR0cHM6Ly9s=
aW5rLmNodGJsLmNvbS9Nb25leS1TdHVmZi1UaGUtUG9kY2FzdA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
B154bc84d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;">check out Money Stuff: The Podcast</a> at Apple, Spotify=
, or wherever you get your podcasts, as one says when one is a podcaster. Y=
ou can <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35003841.25=
7348/aHR0cHM6Ly9saW5rLmNodGJsLmNvbS9Nb25leS1TdHVmZi1UaGUtUG9kY2FzdC10cmFpbG=
Vy/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf3f87a71" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">listen to the trailer</a> now=
, and the first episode will be out tomorrow afternoon.</p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Hedging</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you work at a big public technology company=
, you might get a large chunk of your pay in the form of stock in your comp=
any. Over time, you will accumulate a lot of stock; a lot of your net worth=
 might consist of shares in your company. This is good,=C2=A0this is what t=
he company wants, this aligns incentives: If you own a lot of stock, you wi=
ll work hard so the company does well so your stock will go up.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand, <em>you </em>may not like i=
t.=C2=A0You have a lot of undiversified risk: A lot of your financial net w=
orth is tied up in one company, and a lot of your human capital is tied up =
in that same company, and if the company goes under you will lose everythin=
g. And while it is nice to align incentives, if you are one of thousands of=
 well-paid employees at a large public tech company, there might not be all=
 that much=C2=A0<em>you personally=C2=A0</em>can do to shape the company=E2=
=80=99s destiny.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So you might want to diversify. The easy way t=
o do this is to sell your stock and buy an index fund. Your stock probably =
has vesting periods and restrictions, so you can=E2=80=99t sell all it as s=
oon as you get it, but if you=E2=80=99ve been there a long time you will ha=
ve lots of unrestricted shares and can sell down.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But tech stocks mostly go up, so if you=E2=80=
=99ve been there a long time and are selling shares you got years ago, you =
will have large capital gains. That=E2=80=99s nice for you, really, but it =
does mean you have to pay taxes when you sell your stock and buy index fund=
s.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand, what you could do is:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Start a=C2=A0<em>partnership=C2=A0</em=
>with some other people who happen to own stocks in=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</e=
m>tech companies. There are lots of those people: If you=E2=80=99re a well-=
paid Meta engineer with a bunch of stock, you can probably find well-paid A=
mazon and Alphabet engineers who also own a bunch of their companies=E2=80=
=99 stocks.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">
<em>Contribute=C2=A0</em>your shares to the partnership, in exchange for a =
stake in the partnership. You put in $1 million of Meta stock for 1/3 of th=
e partnership; your friends put in $1 million of Amazon and Alphabet stock =
in exchange for 1/3 stakes in the partnership.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-b=
ottom: 5px;">Now, instead of owning $1 million of Meta stock, you own a one=
-third share in a somewhat more diversified $3 million pot of stocks. (And =
you can expand this to more stocks for more diversification.)</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The advantage is that, while selling your stoc=
k for cash and then reinvesting the cash in an index fund is a taxable tran=
saction, contributing your stock to a partnership in exchange for a share o=
f that partnership is not. And if you do it right, you can make the partner=
ship=E2=80=99s holdings look a lot like an index fund. (Not tax advice! It =
is not in fact quite as simple as this, though this is the right general id=
ea.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: tr=
ansparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is not trivial to do this right,=C2=A0<em>f=
or you: </em>You have to get the technical tax structuring right, plus what=
 are the odds that you know a bunch of other engineers at other companies w=
ith exactly the right amounts of stock to contribute? But with enough well-=
paid engineers at big public tech companies, it is sensible for someone els=
e to do this at scale and offer it as a product. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s <a hre=
f=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35003841.257348/aHR0cHM6=
Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDQtMTEvdGVjaC1taWxsaW9=
uYWlyZXMtY2hhc2UtYmlsbGlvbmFpcmUtdGF4LXNoaWVsZHMtd2l0aC1zd2FwLWZ1bmQ_Y21waW=
Q9QkJEMDQxMTI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZ=
XR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwNDExJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cB681191b7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">
Eliyahu Kamisher reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Known as an exchange fund or a swap fund, the =
product is familiar to the super rich. Now, share-price rallies at companie=
s such as Meta Platforms Inc. and Nvidia Corp. are creating an opportunity =
to offer the structure to moderately wealthy techies as well, says Srikanth=
 Narayan, founder of San Francisco-based Cache.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe mission is to make these financia=
l products =E2=80=93 that have typically been in the upper echelon =E2=80=
=93 available more broadly,=E2=80=9D said Narayan, a former engineer at Ube=
r Technologies Inc. =E2=80=9CAll of my friends and colleagues are talking a=
bout the same thing, which is that more of their net worth is tied up in a =
single stock.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Cache=E2=80=99s swap-fund offering enables par=
ticipants to pool their stock holdings together, creating a more diversifie=
d collection of assets. Investors then get shares of the fund equivalent to=
 their contributions, giving them the benefits of more varied holdings with=
out having to sell their stock.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There=E2=80=99s a limit to how much stock of a=
 particular company Cache can accept because the swap fund is designed to m=
irror the tech-heavy Nasdaq, Narayan said. Currently, he can bring in more =
Amazon.com Inc. and Microsoft Corp. shares, and he=E2=80=99s seeking stock =
from non-tech Nasdaq companies such as PepsiCo Inc. and Costco Wholesale Co=
rp.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here are <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/35003841.257348/aHR0cHM6Ly91c2VjYWNoZS5jb20vcHJvZHVjdC9=
leGNoYW5nZS1mdW5kcw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB128d381d" itemprop=3D"StoryLin=
k" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">more details=
</a> from Cache. Kamisher notes that, if this really takes off (so far it=
=E2=80=99s pretty small), it could be bad for tax revenue; California gets =
a lot of money from tech equity compensation. But that effect depends on wh=
at this product=C2=A0<em>replaces</em>. If it replaces =E2=80=9Csell your s=
tock and buy index funds,=E2=80=9D it will lower tax revenue. If it replace=
s =E2=80=9Cjust hold onto your stock until you retire,=E2=80=9D it won=E2=
=80=99t.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Me, though, I=E2=80=99m more interested in wha=
t it could do for incentives. Presumably the big tech companies pay their e=
mployees with lots of stock (in part for accounting reasons sure but also) =
in order to align incentives and motivate the employees.<a class=3D"footnot=
e-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; =
display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0You would expect that a lot of Meta employees own a lot of Meta s=
tock, a lot of Alphabet employees own a lot of Alphabet stock, a lot of Ama=
zon employees own a lot of Amazon stock and so forth. Each company has empl=
oyees with strong financial incentives =E2=80=94=C2=A0not just the desire f=
or raises and bonuses, but also the desire to increase the value of their e=
xisting stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0to help their company win in the general compe=
tition among tech giants.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But what if all of the midlevel employees of a=
ll of these companies ended up owning diversified portfolios of all of them=
? What if workers in Big Tech were compensated with, effectively, a portfol=
io of Big Tech Index shares? (Plus Costco, if Cache can find any.<a class=
=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !=
important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>) What does that do for competition?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CShould index funds be illegal,=E2=80=
=9D I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35003841.257=
